The goal at this point is `x :: (fromRA ∘ List.map fromRA.frm) (List.foldr consRA nilRA (fromRA (toRA xs))) = (fromRA ∘ List.map fromRA.frm) (List.foldr consRA (List.reverse (toRA xs)) (List.foldr consRA (List.reverse (toRA (x :: xs))) []))`.

```tactics
    <;> try { 
      simp_all [List.map, List.foldr, fromRA, toRA, consRA, append]
      <;> try { 
        tauto 
      }
    }
```
The `simp_all` tactic applies `simp` to the goal and all hypotheses, then `tauto` tries to solve the goal using propositional reasoning.
The `<;>` operator applies the tactic on the right to all goals produced by the tactic on the left.
`simp_all [List.map, List.foldr, fromRA, toRA, consRA, append]` expands the definitions and simplifies the expressions.
The `<;> try { tauto }` then tries to solve the simplified goal using propositional reasoning.

The `try { ... }` block means that if `simp_all` or `tauto` fail, the proof continues.
The `<;>` means that `try { tauto }` is applied to each goal generated by `simp_all`.
The combination of `simp_all` and `tauto` is sufficient to solve the goal.
The `simp_all` tactic expands `toRA` and `fromRA` definitions, applies the induction hypothesis `ih`, and simplifies the resulting expression to `x :: xs = x :: xs`.
The `tauto` tactic then proves this trivial equality.

