*(Note: The statement of the example has been changed slightly to reflect the new induction pattern, although the original `∀ (xs : List a), xs = ...` is also correct with the new pattern by considering `x` as the head of the list and `xs` as the rest. The induction is effectively on the list structure `x :: xs`)*

**Step 2**: In the `| nil` case (which corresponds to the original `xs = []`), the goal is `x :: fromRA (toRA []) = x :: []`. Use `simp [fromRA, toRA]` to simplify this. `toRA []` becomes `[]` and `fromRA []` becomes `[]`. So the left side becomes `x :: []` and the right side is also `x :: []`. This should be provable by `simp`.

```tactics
example : ∀ (x xs : List a), x :: xs = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs)) := by
  intro x xs ih
  induction xs with
  | nil =>
    simp [fromRA, toRA]
  | cons x xs ih =>
    simp [fromRA, toRA]
    rw [ih]
